= La elección robada

It is a municipal election in a state where your work had begun to bite — a mid-size town, a good planilla, polls your people trusted — and the machine performs its whole repertoire on it with the unhurried thoroughness of an orchestra rehearsing: the padrón purged of your colonias, two casillas relocated overnight to addresses that do not exist, urns pregnant by noon, and a final act the count itself, conducted behind a door with your representative outside it.

This was not chance. The semáforo in Bucareli has your file on the *robar* desk now: you are big enough to steal from, and they are practicing — calibrating the alquimia against your networks specifically, learning which of your casilla people can be bought, bullied, or simply relocated. Every technique perfected here is being filed for a larger night.

- @documentar_robo: Document everything: the parallel count, the moved casillas, the padrón surgery — a forensics of the machine.
- @quemar_la_plaza: Make the town ungovernable: occupation of the alcaldía, permanent plantón, the theft made expensive.
- @tragar_robo: Concede quietly. Save the network from exposure; let the town go.

@documentar_robo
go-to: post_event
choose-if: red_casillas >= 10
unavailable-subtitle: Documenting a theft requires eyes at the tables — yours were not there in numbers.
on-arrival: fraude_documentado += 1; fe_voto += 1; political_capital += 2; expediente += 2

The dossier is a small masterpiece of civic accountancy, and its immediate legal effect is precisely nothing — the electoral college certifies its own arithmetic, sincerely. Its real product ships later: your people now know the machine's current repertoire move by move, and the training the next generation of casilla watchers receives is written directly from this town's wounds. The regime rehearsed on you. You took notes.

@quemar_la_plaza
go-to: post_event
choose-if: sup_colonos >= 12 or sup_peasants >= 15
unavailable-subtitle: A plantón needs a base in the town; you organized the vote, not the plaza.
on-arrival: huelgas += 2; sup_peasants += 2; represion += 3; expediente += 4; legitimidad_regimen -= 2; political_capital += 1

The alcaldía acquires a tenant it did not elect: three hundred citizens in shifts, cook fires in the portales, the "elected" presidente municipal sworn in at a hotel two towns away, governing nothing. It will end, eventually, as these always end — a negotiation, a partial concession, a face-saving interinato. But the state's ledger takes the entry it hates most: a theft that had to be paid for twice, once in votes and once in weeks.

@tragar_robo
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: fe_voto -= 2; unity -= 2; sup_middle += 1

The concession speech is dignified and the arithmetic behind it sound: an exposed network is worth more than one town. But the town draws its own conclusion, the one towns always draw, and next time the padrón is purged there will be fewer volunteers to notice: the machine's oldest weapon was never the urn. It is the lesson that resistance is expensive and futile, taught one quiet concession at a time.

@izquierda_oficial
